premise_source_doc_sentence: When exposed to the atmosphere , the pure zinc  (  Zn  )  reacts with oxygen  (  O2  )  to form zinc oxide  (  ZnO  )  , which further reacts with carbon dioxide  (  CO2  )  to form zinc carbonate  (  ZnCO3  )  , a usually dull grey , fairly strong material that protects the steel underneath from further corrosion in many circumstances .
For example , a mixture of 7 % plutonium and 93 % natural uranium reacts similarly , although not identically , to LEU fuel .
It reacts with carbon , halogens , nitrogen , silicon and hydrogen .
It is the process of coating iron and steel with zinc , which alloys with the surface of the base metal when immersing the metal in a bath of molten zinc at a temperature of around 840 F .

This is a unique characteristic for galvanizing , which means that when a galvanized coating is damaged and steel is exposed to the atmosphere , zinc can continue to protect steel through galvanic corrosion  (  often within an annulus of 5 mm , above which electron transfer rate decreases  )  .
